    <h2>Why is surveying crucial?</h2>
    <p>
      After having worked on building map data covering the extensive road networks worldwide, I have come to realize the importance of
      becoming a licensed land surveyor.
    </p>
    <p>
      As I grow older, my desire to spend more time outdoors has strengthened. Maps have always fascinated me, as they offer a glimpse of
      what we know is there, allowing us to explore and discover new perspectives on the world.
    </p>
    <p>
      Land surveying is a profession that wholeheartedly embraces this pursuit. A survey is not just a map; it serves as a crucial tool in
      Civil Engineering and legal documentation, such as land deeds. Precision is of the essence in our measurements, and we take great care
      in stating our level of confidence, accuracy, and precision in our research and observations. When it comes to land development and
      construction, the observations of the surveyor must be spot-on.
    </p>
    <p>
      The meaning of "correct" in a map depends on its purpose. For instance, using OpenStreetMap data for auto navigation, where some
      sections of rural roads may be off by several meters, is acceptable as it's sufficient for successful vehicle navigation. However,
      when it comes to construction, such as paving a road or building a bridge, precise locations of stakes for pavers become critical.
      Construction projects demand meticulous attention to detail and accuracy, and this is where land surveying plays a vital role. To ensure
      the success of such projects, someone needs to be out in the field, making the necessary measurements.
    </p>
